{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778467149558,"sessionID":"ses_1eb198eb3ffe3LeeBAZNTClA3K","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"functions.bash:9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"obo-grep.pl --noheader -r 'ferritin' src/ontology/go-edit.obo | head -30","description":"Search for ferritin-related terms","workdir":"/home/runner/work/eval-ont-agent-go/eval-ont-agent-go"},"output":"[Term]\nid: GO:0008043\nname: obsolete intracellular ferritin complex\nnamespace: cellular_component\ndef: \"OBSOLETE. A ferritin complex located in the cell. Intracellular ferritin complexes contain 24 subunits, in a mixture of L (light) chains and H (heavy) chains.\" [GOC:jl, GOC:mah, PMID:19154717]\ncomment: The reason for obsoletion is that this term represents a cellular component and its location.\nproperty_value: term_tracker_item \"https://github.com/geneontology/go-ontology/issues/27758\" xsd:anyURI\nis_obsolete: true\nreplaced_by: GO:0070288\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0015091\nname: ferric iron transmembrane transporter activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Enables the transfer of ferric iron (Fe(III) or Fe3+) ions from one side of a membrane to the other.\" [ISBN:0198506732]\ncomment: Ferric iron is rarely transported in the free form. Some bacteria have a system in which an outer membrane protein takes iron away from host ferritin or lactoferrin and transport it to a Fe3+ binding protein in the periplasm. The periplasmic protein then delivers the Fe3+ to a transport system located in the cytoplasmic membrane. Consider also GO:0015343 siderophore transmembrane transporter activity.\nintersection_of: GO:0022857 ! transmembrane transporter activity\nintersection_of: has_primary_input CHEBI:29034 ! iron(3+)\nrelationship: part_of GO:0034755 ! iron ion transmembrane transport\n\n[Term]\nid: GO:0070287\nname: ferritin receptor activity\nnamespace: molecular_function\ndef: \"Combining with ferritin, and delivering ferritin into the cell via endocytosis.\" [GOC:bf